results.notes:
On decomposing granite bedrock formation in a mixed oak-pine woodland.

Thallus crustose, with round flat shiny brown areoles with roughened dark margins, K+Y at 100x, no norstictic acid crystals. Apothecia erupting from the margins, becoming sessile, plane to slightly convex, retaining raised margins most of the time. Epihymeniun dark brown, hymeniun and hypothecium hyaline, exciple dark, C-, algae thick across the base.

Spores not found in a small sample of apothecia.

results.notes:
On sandstone bedrock outcrop in semi-arid grassland habitat.

Thallus pale, shiny, tightly adnate, with marginal lobes that have blackened edges and are subdivided into small lobules. Thallus becoming areolate to somewhat lobulate in center. Thallus algal layer divided by medulla hyphae. Heavily afflicted with a red-brown parasite. Apothecia common, lecanorine, thalline margin concolorous with thallus, shiny, thick and raised. Disk red-brown, shiny. Hymenium hyaline, epihymenium thin, red-brown, with small crystals, both the color and crystals soluble in K. Hypothecium hyaline. Algal layer thick across base of apothecia, but jagged. Medulla at base of apothecia with POL+ crystals insoluble in K.

results.notes:
Provisional name created for this unusual/unique collection on 1/3/19.
White stemmed, completely viscid(from top to bottom) orange to viridescent capped Gliophorus with a uniquely solid orange pileipellis. Cap color changing markedly from deep reddish/orange in young fruiting bodies to Deep olive green in both mature and young fruiting bodies; depressed to umbonate caps at maturity( olive green, upturned cap margins). Stems remain white/viscid at maturity(similar to G. flavifolius), but with slight pink/peach tones to extreme stipe base. Caps conical/convex when young,to depressed, slightly umbonate at maturity, with upturned margins(olive green-viridescent at maturity). Caps 1.5-4.5cm(extremely viscid). Pileipellis orange-cutis. Gills=notched, slightly decurrent, light peach in young and mature specimens, close to sub-distant. Stipe= remaining white throughout growth cycle(viscid), small extreme base coloration of light peach in both young and mature specimens. Stipe=3-8cm and viscid. Upon drying cap cuticle(pellicle) deteriorating and peeling away, revealing a constant pink orange pileipellis(color remaining until fully dry). Both young and mature specimens turned deep olive green(similar to Gliophorus psittacinus) on caps only upon drying. Odor=non distinct. Flavor=non distinct. Fruiting abundantly (solely)beneath western red cedar. Microscopy=spores ellipsoid, smooth, clear. 2-4 immature spores to basidia. Basidia aligned slightly parallel to confluent. Herbarium collection to be sequenced with further data. Documented/Type collection observed and collected at Burfoot County Park Olympia, WA, USA on 1/3/19.
